children.subject: Thanks for the response. Which part of 16A is more difficult: the linear algebra or the circuits? I don;t know how difficult/time consuming the circuits part of the course would be; I'll have come in only with very basic understandings of circuits (from physics 7b)

circuits are definitely more difficult than the lin alg. i went in with no experience in lin alg or circuits and did well on lin alg because it's relatively basic but struggled with circuits. since you have some circuit background you may find it better. also wouldn't recommend adding the 3 unit upper div because 61c and 170 have big workloads and ee16a has a problem set and lab of its own that just take up time, but if you're better at handling large loads you may be able to do it
After Math 54, many parts of 16a should be quite easy, so I think it should be completely doable.

history.content:
Will this above schedule be too difficult of a workload? For context, this semester I'm taking 61b + physics 7b + math 54 + r1b (which has been hard but doable) and I plan to take 70 + h/ss over the summer. Does anyone have insight into how my proposed fall schedule might compare this?

Furthermore, would it be foolish to add on a relatively easy 3 unit upper div h/ss to these three classes or should I just go for a decal/1 unit to reach the minimum unit count? I'm also hoping to join a club or two next semester (but like I'll might get rejected lol).
